{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17631457","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17631457"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:28:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:28:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17377"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17377","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17377"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10067"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70216"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10067","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10067"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17377"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55680"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4948"},{"type":"tags","id":"5395"},{"type":"tags","id":"5487"},{"type":"tags","id":"7825"},{"type":"tags","id":"7842"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23564"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23571"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70216","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70216"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA researcher conducts a systematic review examining the effectiveness of a new dietary supplement for weight loss. While searching the literature, they notice that small studies showing weight loss tend to be published in journals, while similar-sized studies showing no effect are often only found in conference abstracts or trial registries.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following types of bias best describes this observation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Selection bias","Information bias","Recall bias","Publication bias","Performance bias"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis scenario demonstrates \u003Cstrong\u003Epublication bias\u003C/strong\u003E, where studies showing positive or statistically significant results are preferentially published in peer-reviewed journals compared to studies with negative or non-significant findings. This systematic distortion leads to an overestimation of treatment effects in the published literature.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe alternative types of bias are not applicable here:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESelection bias\u003C/strong\u003E describes systematic differences in how study participants are chosen or allocated to groups\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInformation bias\u003C/strong\u003E refers to systematic errors in measuring or recording study data\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERecall bias\u003C/strong\u003E occurs when past events are remembered differently between study groups\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPerformance bias\u003C/strong\u003E describes systematic differences in how interventions are delivered to study groups\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPublication bias can be detected using funnel plots in meta-analyses. A symmetrical funnel shape suggests minimal bias, while asymmetry may indicate that smaller negative studies are missing from the published literature. This highlights the importance of searching grey literature and trial registries when conducting systematic reviews.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Publication bias distorts the scientific literature when studies with statistically significant results are more likely to be published than those with non-significant findings.","Small studies with positive results are more likely to appear in peer-reviewed journals compared to similar studies with negative results.","Funnel plot analysis in meta-analyses can help identify potential publication bias by examining the relationship between study size and effect size."],"references":["Sullivan LM. Essentials of biostatistics in public health. 3rd ed. Burlington (MA): Jones \u0026 Bartlett Learning; 2018.","Dawson B, Trapp RG. Basic \u0026 clinical biostatistics. 4th ed. New York: McGraw-Hill; 2004."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55680"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17377"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55680","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55680"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-14T09:37:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-14T09:40:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10067"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70216"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","po